bit_size returns the number of bits used to represent an integer.

bit_size(0)       = 32
bit_size(0_1)     = 8
bit_size(0_2)     = 16
bit_size(0_4)     = 32
bit_size(0_8)     = 64

scalar examples:
a(i) = 0  bit_size(a(i)) = 32
a(i) = 1  bit_size(a(i)) = 32
a(i) = -1  bit_size(a(i)) = 32
a(i) = 2147483647  bit_size(a(i)) = 32

huge examples:
huge(0)   = 2147483647  bit_size = 32
huge(0_1) = 127  bit_size = 8
huge(0_2) = 32767  bit_size = 16
huge(0_4) = 2147483647  bit_size = 32
huge(0_8) = 9223372036854775807  bit_size = 64
